{
  "result": "In the old quarter of my coastal city, dawn arrives like a patient musician tuning instruments behind cracked stucco walls. Streetlamps surrender their amber halos, and fishermen haul baskets of sardines across mosaics slick with salt and gossip. I walk the alleyways with a notebook I rarely open, preferring to memorize the small theatre of everyday collisions. Two bakers argue about the proper heat for sesame bread, their hands dusted white as snow that never falls here. A retired lighthouse keeper tells a child how beams once sliced fog like scimitars, saving ships, betraying smugglers. He laughs when the child asks if the moon receives a salary for working nights. Nearby, a graffiti mural shifts colors as the sun rises higher, revealing a portrait of a woman whose eyes are borrowed from the sea. She was a poet who stitched her verses onto kite tails, insisting that words should feel the pull of the wind before settling on the page. Today I buy a kite at the market, red paper stretched across crossed bamboo, and write only a single sentence: \u201cReturn if there\u2019s news of rain.\u201d When the afternoon breeze arrives, swollen with distant thunder, I climb the steps to the abandoned fort and let the kite rise, the string humming like a restless violin. Below me the city exhales, a mosaic of roofs and whispered secrets, while the kite tugs toward storm clouds that promise change, or perhaps simply the mercy of cool, unscripted rain. I wait, listening closely.",
